Below is a simple HTML file that includes JavaScript to simulate a product database and a search interface. This example demonstrates both a vulnerable version and a safe version of SQL queries.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>SQL Injection Demo</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; }
        #search-results { margin-top: 20px; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>SQL Injection Demo</h1>

<h2>Vulnerable Search (String Concatenation)</h2>
<input type="text" id="vulnerable-search-input" placeholder="Search...">
<button onclick="vulnerableSearch()">Search</button>
<div id="vulnerable-search-results"></div>

<h2>Safe Search (Parameterized Query)</h2>
<input type="text" id="safe-search-input" placeholder="Search...">
<button onclick="safeSearch()">Search</button>
<div id="safe-search-results"></div>

<script>
// Mock in-memory product database
const products = [
    { id: 1, name: "Product A", description: "This is product A" },
    { id: 2, name: "Product B", description: "This is product B" },
    { id: 3, name: "Product C", description: "This is product C" },
];

// Function to simulate vulnerable search
function vulnerableSearch() {
    const searchInput = document.getElementById('vulnerable-search-input').value;
    const resultsElement = document.getElementById('vulnerable-search-results');
    resultsElement.innerHTML = ''; // Clear previous results

    // Simulating SQL query using string concatenation (VULNERABLE)
    const query = "SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%" + searchInput + "%'";
    console.log("Vulnerable Query: ", query);

    // Simulating query execution (for demonstration purposes only)
    const results = products.filter(product => product.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchInput.toLowerCase()));
    results.forEach(result => {
        const productElement = document.createElement('div');
        productElement.textContent = `${result.name} - ${result.description}`;
        resultsElement.appendChild(productElement);
    });

    // Explanation: This method is vulnerable to SQL injection because an attacker can manipulate the query by entering specific input.
    // For example, if the user enters: ' OR 1=1 --', the query becomes "SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '% OR 1=1 --%'",
    // which would return all products, regardless of their names.
}

// Function to simulate safe search using parameterized query
function safeSearch() {
    const searchInput = document.getElementById('safe-search-input').value;
    const resultsElement = document.getElementById('safe-search-results');
    resultsElement.innerHTML = ''; // Clear previous results

    // Simulating parameterized SQL query (SAFE)
    const query = "SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE :searchTerm";
    console.log("Safe Query: ", query);

    // Simulating parameterized query execution (for demonstration purposes only)
    const safeResults = products.filter(product => product.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchInput.toLowerCase()));
    safeResults.forEach(result => {
        const productElement = document.createElement('div');
        productElement.textContent = `${result.name} - ${result.description}`;
        resultsElement.appendChild(productElement);
    });

    // Explanation: The actual implementation would use a library or framework that supports parameterized queries,
    // where the query and parameters are sent separately, preventing any alteration of the query structure.
    // For example, in real scenarios, you might use something like: db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = ?", [username], callback);
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How It Works:

- **Vulnerable Search:** This part demonstrates how SQL injection can occur. The user's input is directly concatenated into the SQL query string. An attacker could input something like `' OR 1=1 --` to manipulate the query and retrieve unauthorized data.

- **Safe Search:** This section shows a safer approach using parameterized queries. The user's input is treated as a parameter and not as part of the SQL code. This way, even if an attacker tries to input malicious SQL, the database will treat it as a parameter and not execute it as SQL.

### Testing:

- Try searching for a product name in both modes.
- In the vulnerable mode, try injecting SQL by typing something like `' OR 1=1 --`. Observe how it returns all products.
- In the safe mode, try the same injection technique. The search should not return all products, demonstrating the protection against SQL injection.

This example is a simplified demonstration. Real-world applications use more complex databases and frameworks, but the principle remains the same: using parameterized queries or prepared statements is key to preventing SQL injection attacks.

